 Building the Merkle tree is a problem which seems 
simple until one attempts to make it fast. At small scales it is fine 
on the CPU, but the moment leaf counts climb into the tens of 
thousands — which is routine in any active blockchain or 
certificate log — the sequential SHA-256 hashing becomes a 
genuine bottleneck. This paper describes a CUDA implementation 
that addresses that gap by hashing all leaves at once on a GPU 
using real SHA-256, not a placeholder. The design uses shared 
memory tiling inside both the leaf and tree-level kernels, with 
Thrust handling device buffer management and CUDA Events 
measuring every stage precisely. Running on an NVIDIA Tesla T4 
with 18,674 leaves extracted from an actual IEEE paper, it finishes 
in under 2 ms compared to 78 ms on CPU — a 68.7× speedup — 
and processes 13.8 million leaves per second. Both kernels hit 
100% theoretical occupancy. The GPU output was checked byte
for-byte against Python hashlib to confirm the SHA-256 
implementation is correct, including the two-block padding case 
that catches out a lot of GPU hash implementations. 
